 <h2>Part 10</h2>
 <p>Len Phan wants the  LuckyTire database to include an easy-to-use switchboard interface. You&rsquo;ll  create the interface by completing the following:</p>
 <ol start="1" type="1">
   <li>Open the <strong>LuckyTire </strong>database.</li>
 </ol>
 <ol start="2" type="1">
   <li>Change the database&rsquo;s window style to       overlapping windows.</li>
 </ol>
 <ol start="3" type="1">
   <li>Design and create a form named <strong>frmQueriesDialogBox</strong>. Use the       figure below and the following descriptions as a guide to create the form.</li>
 </ol>
 <p>&nbsp;</p>
 <p align="center"><img src="Homework10_clip_image001.jpg" alt="" width="430" height="383" /></p>
 <ol start="3" type="1">
   <ol start="1" type="a">
     <li>Place the text <strong>Queries </strong>in the form&rsquo;s title bar. Set the following properties        for the form: set Record Selectors to No; Navigation Buttons to No; Auto        Resize to No; Close Button to No; Modal to yes; and Shortcut Menu to No.</li>
   </ol>
 </ol>
 <ol start="3" type="1">
   <ol start="2" type="a">
     <li>A list box with a Name property value of <strong>lstQueryList </strong>displays all the        query names contained in the LuckyTire database, excluding those queries        that start with a &ldquo;~&rdquo; character. To place the query names in the list        box, use an SQL SELECT statement to retrieve the query names from the        MSysObjects table, and display the queries in query name order. Delete        the label attached to the list box, and widen the list box to        approximately 2.5 inches.</li>
   </ol>
 </ol>
 <ol start="3" type="1">
   <ol start="3" type="a">
     <li>Use the heading <strong>Available Queries</strong>, formatted with a 14-point, bold font,        above the list box.</li>
   </ol>
 </ol>
 <ol start="3" type="1">
   <ol start="4" type="a">
     <li>Three command buttons appear below the list        box. The left command button displays the Preview icon above the word <strong>Preview</strong>, the middle command        button displays the MS Access Query icon above the word <strong>Display</strong>, and the right command        button displays the CloseWindow icon above the word <strong>Close</strong>. Double-clicking a query name has the same effect as        selecting a query name in the list box and clicking the middle command        button. Both events cause Access to display the query datasheet for the        selected query. Clicking the left command button opens the selected query        in Print Preview. (You will add the VBA code for these events in the        tutorial project for Tutorial 11. For now, double-clicking or clicking        should cause no action to occur.) Clicking the Close command button causes        Access to close the dialog box.</li>
   </ol>
 </ol>
 <ol start="3" type="1">
   <ol start="5" type="a">
     <li>Resize the form&rsquo;s Detail section in Design        view, and then resize the form in Form view. Set the form&rsquo;s Border Style        to Dialog, with the following properties: Auto Center is Yes; Fit to        Screen is No; and Scroll Bars is Neither. Set the background color to        Green in the Standard Colors gallery. Set the background color of the        list box to Green 3.</li>
   </ol>
 </ol>
 <ol start="4" type="1">
   <li>Create a macro group named <strong>mcrSwitchboardMacros </strong>that contains macros to be used with two       of the command buttons in the switchboard you&rsquo;ll create in the next step.       The two macros perform these actions: close the switchboard, and close the       switchboard and exit Access.</li>
 </ol>
 <ol start="5" type="1">
   <li>Design and create a Switchboard form named <strong>LuckyTire</strong>. Use the figure below       and the following descriptions as a guide to create the switchboard.<br />
    <strong>Note</strong>:  Follow <a href="SwitchBoardManager.htm">these directions to enable the Switchboard Manager</a> in the Quick Access Toolbar (QAT) </li>
 </ol>
 <p>&nbsp;</p>
 <p align="center"><img src="Homework10_clip_image002.jpg" alt="" width="489" height="284" /></p>
 <ol start="5" type="1">
   <ol start="1" type="a">
     <li>Use the Switchboard Manager to create the        switchboard. Place the command buttons on the form; the last two command        buttons should use the macros in the <strong>mcrSwitchboardMacros </strong>macro group. The first three command buttons should switch to the        Forms switchboard page, switch to the Reports switchboard page, and open        the frmQueriesDialogBox form in edit mode.</li>
   </ol>
 </ol>
 <ol start="5" type="1">
   <ol start="2" type="a">
     <li>The Forms switchboard page should open the        frmTireOrders form in edit mode, open the frmCustomer form in edit mode,        open the frmTires form in edit mode, and return to the main switchboard.</li>
   </ol>
 </ol>
 <ol start="5" type="1">
   <ol start="3" type="a">
     <li>The Reports switchboard page should have three        options to open each of the three reports, a fourth option to open the        Customer Mailing Labels, and a fifth option to return to the main switchboard.</li>
   </ol>
 </ol>
 <ol start="5" type="1">
   <ol start="4" type="a">
     <li>Set the background color for the switchboard        to Green 5, delete the Form Footer section, resize the switchboard in        Form view, and then set the following form properties: Auto Resize to No;        Close Button to No; and Border Style to Dialog.</li>
   </ol>
 </ol>
 <ol start="6" type="1">
   <li>Save the Switchboard form, and then test the       command buttons on the main switchboard page, the other switchboard pages,       and the frmQueriesDialogBox form to make sure that your switchboard items       work correctly. If necessary, return to the Switchboard Manager and make       any corrections.</li>
 </ol>
